esc>Attribute information</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcCitatn><resTitle>U.S. Census Bureau Releases 2010 Census Population Counts for the U.S. Virgin Islands</resTitle><resAltTitle>Census 2010 USVI Population</resAltTitle><date><pubDate>2011-08-24</pubDate></date><citRespParty><rpOrgName>United States Census Bureau</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo><cntAddress><delPoint>Suitland, MD</delPoint></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><role><RoleCd value="010"/></role></citRespParty><citRespParty><rpOrgName>United States Census Bureau</rpOrgName><role><RoleCd value="006"/></role></citRespParty><citOnlineRes><linkage>http://www.census.gov/2010census/news/releases/operations/cb11-cn180.html</linkage></citOnlineRes></srcCitatn><srcExt><exDesc>Ground condition</exDesc><tempEle><TempExtent><exTemp><TM_Instant><tmPosition>2010-01-01</tmPosition></TM_Instant></exTemp></TempExtent></tempEle></srcExt></dataSource><prcStep><stepDesc>The 1:1,000,000-scale county and State boundaries were derived from U.S. Census TIGER (Topologically Integrated Geographic Encoding and Reference system) data. The TIGER files were merged and generalized. County boundaries within States were removed using the ESRI dissolve tool.</stepDesc><stepDateTm>2007-01-01</stepDateTm><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Bound_Cen06</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>All the 1:1,000,000-scale map layers were checked for vertical integration. Line positions were adjusted as necessary to remove overlaps. Wherever possible, linear features were separated by 300 meters, but were kept within 500 meters of their true location.</stepDesc><stepDateTm>2012-01-01</stepDateTm><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>QC</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="produced"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>National Atlas 1M States 2012</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>The areas in the file were combined into large polygons, one for each State including associated islands, and for States that border the Great Lakes, one for the water area of each State. Population values were added from the 2010 Census information. The data were projected by region to the National Atlas Albers Equal Area Conic projection, fields were added for the perimeter measurement and square miles, the values were calculated using ArcMap, and the data were converted back to geographic coordinates. The Albers Equal Area Conic parameters used are available on request.</stepDesc><stepDateTm>2013-01-01</stepDateTm><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Census 2010 USVI Population</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Census 2010 Population</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>The map layer was saved in shapefile and in file geodatabase formats.</stepDesc><stepDateTm>2013-01-01</stepDateTm></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>Data along the Canadian border were adjusted so that the Canadian and U.S. 1:1,000,000-scale data sets can be used together as seamlessly as possible. Problem areas were identified by Natural Resources Canada (NRCan) and edits to the U.S. data were performed by the USGS. To identify problems, the National Atlas 1M States 2012 data set was projected to the NRCan working coordinate system, which is a Lambert Conformal Conic projection with standard parallels of 49 and 77 degrees, datum of NAD83, an XY tolerance of 0.001 meters, and an XY resolution of 0.0001 meters. The Canadian and U.S. data sets were displayed together and features were compared across the border. An initial set of comments and suggestions for edits were sent to the USGS by NRCan. NRCan used satellite imagery for reference during the editing process by converting the appropriate National Atlas 1:1,000,000-scale map layers and the 250K Canadian topographic data to KML and loading the KMLs into GoogleEarth. Using the cursor coordinates in the ArcMap status bar, NRCan visually navigated and correlated the ArcMap and GoogleEarth vectors. NRCan exported their findings and sent them to the USGS for correction and (or) further comment. USGS reviewed the Canadian findings and returned the data to NRCan with comments. The U.S. data were either edited, not edited and further explanation was requested, or not edited and changes were suggested for the Canadian data. This process was repeated until both NRCan and USGS felt that the data were satisfactorily harmonized.</stepDesc><stepDateTm>2013-01-01</stepDateTm><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Can_US_Boundary 2009</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Canada 250K Topo</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Can_US_Boundary 2011</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>Canada Boundary</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>National Atlas 1M States 2012</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resAltTitle>QC</resAltTitle></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep></dataLineage></dqInfo><spatRepInfo><Indref>U.S. Department of Commerce; 2013; American National Standards Institute (ANSI) Codes for States, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the Insular Areas of the United States; U.S. Census Bureau.</Indref><VectSpatRep><geometObjs Name="US_States"><geoObjTyp><GeoObjTypCd value="002" Sync="TRUE"></GeoObjTypCd></geoObjTyp><geoObjCnt Sync="TRUE">0</geoObjCnt></geometObjs><topLvl><TopoLevCd value="001" Sync="TRUE"></TopoLevCd></topLvl></VectSpatRep></spatRepInfo><eainfo><detailed Name="US_States"><enttyp><enttypl Sync="TRUE">US_States</enttypl><enttypd>A first order division of the nation, including States and State equivalents.</enttypd><enttypds>National Atlas of the United States</enttypds><enttypt Sync="TRUE">Feature Class</enttypt><enttypc Sync="TRUE">0</enttypc></enttyp><attr><attrlabl Sync="TRUE">FID</attrlabl><attalias Sy